The Senate yesterday passed the Federal Capital Territory Administration’s (FCT) 2019 budget of N243,374,511,077.00. Out of the total budget, N55,043,425,247.00 is for Personnel Costs and the sum of N57,610,188,661.00 only, is for Overhead Cost while the balance of N130,720,897,169.00 only, is for Capital Projects. The Bill, which was presented on the floor of the Senate for consideration by the Senate Leader, Sen. Ahmed Lawan during plenary, was eventually passed after second and third readings. The Bill is for the service of the Federal Capital Territory, Abuja for the financial year commencing from 1st January and ending 31st December. The Senate has also approved the sum of $266 million as contained in the 2016-2018 external borrowing plan of President Muhammadu Buhari for Niger State Development Policy Operation (DPO). The approval followed the recommendation of the Senate Committee on Local and Foreign Debts. Presenting the report, the Committee chairman, Senator Shehu Sani said that the fund for DPO from the World Bank is proposed to finance key programmes of the government of Niger State, aimed at stimulating internally generated revenue and develop critical infrastructure that will attract private investors to the state and thus increase employment opportunities to residents and citizens. He explained that “the World Bank Development Policy Operation (DPO) is a budget-support facility to finance budget gaps that governments often encounter in implementing their annual budgets.” LEADERSHIP recalls that the Senate had on July 27, 2017 and November 9, 2017 during its sittings, mandated the committee to consider the Niger State DPO as contained in the 2016-2018 approved external borrowing plan, following its approval of the loans’ request for a total of seven states. In its findings and observations, the Senate Committee pointed out that the credit facility has an attractive low financing data of 1.25 per cent interest; moratorium of five years and a 25 years maturity tenor. The committee, in its report said: “According to the latest Debt Management Office figures, Niger State has a total debt stock of $232.1 million.” The committee said that “approving the current loan request of $266 million for Niger State will bring its total debt stock to $498.1 million.” 